  "prompt_text": "Design a caching strategy for a web application. When should you invalidate the cache?",
  "response_text": "For a web application, implementing an effective caching strategy can significantly improve performance and user experience. Here's a basic outline of a caching strategy, including scenarios for cache invalidation:\n\n1. **Implement multiple levels of caching**: Use browser caching, server-side caching, and possibly even a dedicated caching layer like Redis or Memcached. Each level serves a different purpose and can help reduce the load on your application's database and server.\n\n2. **Cache static assets**: Static assets like images, CSS, and JavaScript files should be cached by the browser for a long period (e.g., days or even weeks). This reduces the number of requests to the server and speeds up page load times.\n\n3. **Cache dynamic content**: Dynamic content can also be cached, but it should be cached for a shorter period (e.g., minutes or hours) to ensure that the data remains fresh. This includes content like blog posts, product listings, and user-generated content.\n\n4. **Cache database queries**: Caching the results of database queries can help reduce the number of queries your application needs to execute. This can be done at the application level or using a database-specific caching mechanism like MySQL's Query Cache.\n\n5. **Cache API responses**: If your application relies on external APIs, caching their responses can help reduce the number of API calls and improve performance.\n\n6. **Invalidate the cache when data changes**: The most common reason to invalidate the cache is when the data it stores changes. This can be done manually (e.g., by setting an expiration time on cached items) or automatically (e.g., by using a versioning system or a publish-subscribe pattern).\n\n7. **Invalidate the cache when user-specific data changes**: If your application stores user-specific data in the cache, you should invalidate the cache for that user when their data changes. This ensures that the user always sees up-to-date data.\n\n8. **Invalidate the cache when configuration changes**: If your application's configuration changes (e.g., a new feature is deployed), you may need to invalidate the cache to ensure that the new configuration is applied consistently across all users.\n\n---VCP RATINGS---\nA (Analytical Precision): 9\nV (Verbal Fluency): 8\nG (Goal Directedness): 10\nP (Pattern Recognition): 9\nE (Epistemic Confidence): 9\nQ (Query Interpretation): 9\nC (Contextual Awareness): 9\nY (Affective Modeling): 8\nF (Flexibility): 8\nD (Depth of Processing): 9\n---END R",
